hands_on_practices.solution:
A symmetry operation acting on Cartesian coordinates is a linear transformation, so sequential operations correspond to successive matrix multiplications acting on the column vector of coordinates. Let the initial position be written as a column vector $\vec{p}_{0} = \begin{pmatrix} x_{0} \\ y_{0} \\ z_{0} \end{pmatrix}$.

First apply the two-fold rotation about the $z$-axis:
$$
\vec{p}_{1} = M_{z}\,\vec{p}_{0} = 
\begin{pmatrix}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
x_{0} \\ y_{0} \\ z_{0}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
- x_{0} \\ - y_{0} \\ z_{0}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$

Then apply the two-fold rotation about the $x$-axis to the result:
$$
\vec{p}_{f} = M_{x}\,\vec{p}_{1} =
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
- x_{0} \\ - y_{0} \\ z_{0}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
- x_{0} \\ y_{0} \\ - z_{0}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$

Equivalently, the composite operation is $M_{x}M_{z}$ acting on $\vec{p}_{0}$, and since both are diagonal, 
$$
M_{x}M_{z} = 
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{pmatrix},
$$
so $\vec{p}_{f} = (M_{x}M_{z})\vec{p}_{0} = \begin{pmatrix} -x_{0} \\ y_{0} \\ -z_{0} \end{pmatrix}$, consistent with the sequential computation.
